value.value: The round end of the long bones.

A self-limited benign neoplasm characterized by a zonal architecture. It is composed of spindle cells oriented randomly or in short intersecting fascicles. Peripherally, the spindle cells merge with osteoblasts that rim and populate ill-defined trabeculae and sheets of unmineralized woven bone, which is surrounded by well-formed trabecular and cortical-type bone that remodels into lamellar bone. Treatment is usually simple excision. Prognosis is excellent; recurrence is uncommon. (WHO 2020)
A region of cell-cell contact between adjacent cells in an epithelial layer.
The finger-like projections that increase the surface area of the apical membrane of the thin layer of tissue that covers organs, glands, and other structures within the body.
A structure created by the folding over of the thin layer of tissue that covers organs, glands, and other structures within the body.
A hollow area in the upper portion of the tympanic cavity.
The small bundles of smooth muscle connected to hair follicles that cause the hair to stand straight creating 'goose bumps.'
Any of several arteries that arise from the aorta and supply blood to the esophagus.
The small, compound, unbranched exocrine glands varying in number that are located within the submucosa of the esophagus.
An epithelial cell that covers the lower third of the esophageal lumen. It is also found in the submucosal glands of the esophagus.
The lining of the esophagus. It is composed of non-keratinized stratified squamous epithelium, lamina propria, and muscularis mucosa.
A benign soft tissue neoplasm characterized by the presence of neoplastic spindle and stellate cells, and vascular proliferation in a myxoid stroma.
The layer of muscularis mucosa in the esophageal wall. It is thicker than the muscularis mucosa of the stomach and intestine. It is composed of longitudinal muscle fibers.
A hole in the right crus of the diaphragm through which the esophagus and vagus nerve pass.
A flat, scale-like epithelial cell that lines the upper and middle third of the esophageal lumen.
The tissue of the esophageal wall. It is composed of mucosa, a muscular coat, and a serosal surface.

An embryological structure found at the junction of the inferior vena cava and the right atrium, which, during gestation, functions to direct the flow of blood from the right atrium into the left atrium via the foramen ovale.
A synapse in which the firing of the presynaptic cell increases the probability of firing of the postsynaptic cell.

An enzyme producing region of the pancreatic tissue containing the pancreatic acini and exocrine intralobular ducts which collectively secrete the digestive enzymes into the main pancreatic duct to drain into the duodenal part of the small intestine.

An opening in the aponeurosis of the external oblique muscle of the abdominal wall through which the spermatic cord (males), round ligament (females), ilioinguinal nerve, and genitofemoral nerve's genital branch pass.
A ring of striated muscular fibers surrounding the anus on the outside of the internal anal sphincter.
A tube extending from the middle ear to the outer ear.
An infiltrating malignant soft tissue neoplasm characterized by the presence of immature undifferentiated cells and abundant myxoid stroma formation.

A thin lamina of white matter comprising long association fibers located between the claustrum and putamen in the brain, and which connects the midportion of the superotemporal region with the midportion of the ventral and lateral aspects of the prefrontal cortex.
An artery arising from the common carotid artery at the level of the upper border of the thyroid cartilage that ascends the neck forming eight different branches.
Any artery arising from the external carotid artery.
A blood vessel arising from the profunda artery supplying the muscles on the front of the thigh and divides into ascending, descending and transverse branches.

label.value: External Cuneiform Bone of the Foot

value.value: The third or lateral wedge-shaped bone in the distal row of the tarsus.
A thin layer of fibrous tissue capable of stretching and contracting. It is part of the tunica media of the blood vessels.
The lateral of a pair of small oval masses that protrude slightly from the posteroinferior aspect of the thalamus; commonly considered a part of the metathalamus.

label.value: External Granular Layer of the Cerebral Cortex

value.value: The second layer of the cerebral cortex, composed of many small pyramidal cells and granule cells with short axons.
An artery arising from the bifurcation of the common iliac artery in the lower torso. The external iliac artery becomes the femoral artery and is the main blood supply for the leg.
Any artery arising from the external iliac artery.
A soft and painless polypoid mass that arises from the mucosa in the nasal cavity.  It is usually the result of an inflammatory process.  It may recur following surgical resection.
A vein in the lower torso accompanying the external iliac artery that connects the femoral vein with the common iliac vein.
The most superficial of the three intercostal muscles (external, internal, innermost) found in the intercostal space, which aid in both active and passive inhalation.
A large superficial vein in the neck that empties into the subclavian vein.

label.value: External Lateral Ligament of the Ankle

value.value: A ligament consisting of three distinct fasciculi including the anterior, middle and posterior fasciculi.
The bony prominence on the outside of the ankle formed by the distal end of the fibula.
An artery on the lateral side of the ankle arising from the anterior tibial artery.
The outer portion of the nose that protrudes from the face.
The largest and most superficial muscle on the lateral side of the anterior abdomen which compresses the abdomen and pulls the chest downward.
The deep, one inch long portion of the parieto-occipital fissure, a groove, on the outer surface of the cerebral cortex midway between the occipital lobe and the fissure of Rolando.
An artery supplying blood to the bottom of the feet and toes that arises from the posterior tibial artery.

A benign or malignant neoplasm affecting the nasopharynx. Representative examples of benign neoplasms include angiofibroma and squamous papilloma. Representative examples of malignant neoplasms include keratinizing squamous cell carcinoma and nonkeratinizing carcinoma.
A two headed (inferior and superior) muscle attached to the mandible that opens the jaw and brings it forward.

label.value: External Pyramidal Cell Layer of the Cerebral Cortex

value.value: The third layer of the cerebral cortex, composed of an inner zone of medium sized pyramid-shaped cells with a single apical dendrite extending outward toward the surface and several dendrites extending inward and an outer zone of larger pyramid shaped cells whose dendrites and axons extend beyond this layer.
